{
  "format": "tiptap/v1",
  "doc": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Structured output APIs constrain the model's output to a specific data schema — a JSON object with defined fields, types, and constraints — rather than free text. This eliminates the fragile post-processing step of parsing an LLM's natural-language response into structured data, and is essential for building reliable pipelines where downstream code depends on a predictable output shape."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Why Structured Output Matters"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When a model's output is consumed by application code — database writes, API calls, UI rendering — the application expects a specific structure. Free-text output requires the application to parse, validate, and handle errors from the parsing step, all of which can fail in unpredictable ways. Structured output moves the enforcement to the model API layer, making the output reliable by construction."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Three Approaches Compared"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Three approaches to structured output: prompt-only (unreliable, requires parsing), JSON mode (valid JSON but schema not enforced), JSON Schema with strict=true (schema enforced server-side, no post-processing needed)"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "OpenAI: JSON Mode"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "JSON mode guarantees that the model's output is parseable as JSON but does not enforce a specific schema. The application still needs to validate that the fields are correct. It is enabled by passing ",
            "marks": []
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "response_format={\"type\": \"json_object\"}",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " and describing the desired structure in the system prompt."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import openai\nimport json\n\nclient = openai.OpenAI()\n\nresponse = client.chat.completions.create(\n    model=\"gpt-4o-mini\",\n    response_format={\"type\": \"json_object\"},\n    messages=[\n        {\n            \"role\": \"system\",\n            \"content\": (\n                \"Extract the following fields from the user's text and return them as JSON: \"\n                \"name (string), age (integer), city (string). \"\n                \"If a field is absent, use null.\"\n            ),\n        },\n        {\n            \"role\": \"user\",\n            \"content\": \"My name is Alice and I am 30 years old. I live in Berlin.\",\n        },\n    ],\n    temperature=0.0,\n)\n\ndata = json.loads(response.choices[0].message.content)\nprint(data)\n# → {'name': 'Alice', 'age': 30, 'city': 'Berlin'}\n\n# JSON mode only guarantees valid JSON, not schema conformance.\n# Always validate the returned object:\nassert isinstance(data.get(\"age\"), int), \"age must be an integer\"\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "OpenAI: Structured Outputs with JSON Schema"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "OpenAI's Structured Outputs feature (available on gpt-4o and later) enforces a full JSON Schema server-side, including field names, types, required fields, and enum values. The model is constrained at the token level and cannot produce output that violates the schema. Set ",
            "marks": []
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "strict: True",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " inside the schema object to enable this guarantee."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import openai\nimport json\n\nclient = openai.OpenAI()\n\nSCHEMA = {\n    \"type\": \"object\",\n    \"properties\": {\n        \"name\":  {\"type\": \"string\"},\n        \"age\":   {\"type\": \"integer\"},\n        \"city\":  {\"type\": [\"string\", \"null\"]},\n    },\n    \"required\": [\"name\", \"age\", \"city\"],\n    \"additionalProperties\": False,\n}\n\nresponse = client.chat.completions.create(\n    model=\"gpt-4o-mini\",\n    response_format={\n        \"type\": \"json_schema\",\n        \"json_schema\": {\n            \"name\": \"person_extraction\",\n            \"strict\": True,\n            \"schema\": SCHEMA,\n        },\n    },\n    messages=[\n        {\"role\": \"system\", \"content\": \"Extract person details from the user's text.\"},\n        {\"role\": \"user\",   \"content\": \"Alice is 30 and lives in Berlin.\"},\n    ],\n    temperature=0.0,\n)\n\ndata = json.loads(response.choices[0].message.content)\nprint(data)\n# → {'name': 'Alice', 'age': 30, 'city': 'Berlin'}\n# Schema is guaranteed — no validation needed\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Using Pydantic with OpenAI Structured Outputs"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The OpenAI Python SDK's ",
            "marks": []
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "parse()",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " helper accepts a Pydantic model, generates the JSON Schema automatically, and deserialises the response into a typed Python object — eliminating manual schema authoring and JSON parsing."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# pip install openai pydantic\nimport openai\nfrom pydantic import BaseModel\n\nclient = openai.OpenAI()\n\n\nclass Person(BaseModel):\n    name: str\n    age: int\n    city: str | None = None\n\n\ncompletion = client.beta.chat.completions.parse(\n    model=\"gpt-4o-mini\",\n    messages=[\n        {\"role\": \"system\", \"content\": \"Extract person details from the user's text.\"},\n        {\"role\": \"user\",   \"content\": \"Alice is 30 and lives in Berlin.\"},\n    ],\n    response_format=Person,\n)\n\nperson = completion.choices[0].message.parsed  # already a Person instance\nprint(person.name, person.age, person.city)     # Alice 30 Berlin\nprint(type(person))                             # <class '__main__.Person'>\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Anthropic: Tool-Use Pattern for Structured Output"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Anthropic's Messages API does not have a native JSON schema enforcement mode. The idiomatic pattern is to define a tool whose input schema matches the desired output structure, and force the model to call that tool by setting ",
            "marks": []
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "tool_choice",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " to the tool's name. The model's tool call parameters are guaranteed to match the schema because Anthropic validates tool call arguments server-side."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import anthropic\nimport json\n\nclient = anthropic.Anthropic()\n\n# Define the desired output structure as a tool\nEXTRACT_TOOL = {\n    \"name\": \"extract_person\",\n    \"description\": \"Extract person details from the input text.\",\n    \"input_schema\": {\n        \"type\": \"object\",\n        \"properties\": {\n            \"name\": {\"type\": \"string\", \"description\": \"Full name of the person\"},\n            \"age\":  {\"type\": \"integer\", \"description\": \"Age in years\"},\n            \"city\": {\"type\": \"string\",  \"description\": \"City of residence, or null if unknown\"},\n        },\n        \"required\": [\"name\", \"age\", \"city\"],\n    },\n}\n\nresponse = client.messages.create(\n    model=\"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001\",\n    max_tokens=256,\n    tools=[EXTRACT_TOOL],\n    tool_choice={\"type\": \"tool\", \"name\": \"extract_person\"},  # force the tool call\n    messages=[{\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": \"Alice is 30 and lives in Berlin.\"}],\n)\n\n# The response content contains the tool_use block\nfor block in response.content:\n    if block.type == \"tool_use\":\n        data = block.input  # already a dict matching the schema\n        print(data)\n        # → {'name': 'Alice', 'age': 30, 'city': 'Berlin'}\n        break\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Anthropic: Assistant Prefill Pattern"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A lighter alternative is to pre-fill the assistant's response with the opening brace, which forces the model to continue generating a JSON object. The model cannot abandon the JSON mode once the brace is placed. This must be paired with a validation step and retry logic since schema conformance is not guaranteed."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import anthropic\nimport json\n\nclient = anthropic.Anthropic()\n\n\ndef extract_with_prefill(\n    text: str,\n    schema_description: str,\n    retries: int = 3,\n) -> dict:\n    \"\"\"\n    Extract structured data using the assistant-prefill trick.\n    Validates the output and retries on schema violations.\n    \"\"\"\n    for attempt in range(retries):\n        response = client.messages.create(\n            model=\"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001\",\n            max_tokens=512,\n            system=(\n                f\"Extract the following fields as JSON: {schema_description}. \"\n                \"Output ONLY JSON, no other text.\"\n            ),\n            messages=[\n                {\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": text},\n                # Pre-fill the assistant with '{' to start JSON immediately\n                {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": \"{\"},\n            ],\n        )\n        # Reconstruct the full JSON string (the model continued after '{')\n        json_text = \"{\" + response.content[0].text\n        try:\n            data = json.loads(json_text)\n            return data\n        except json.JSONDecodeError:\n            if attempt == retries - 1:\n                raise ValueError(f\"Could not parse JSON after {retries} attempts: {json_text}\")\n    return {}\n\n\nresult = extract_with_prefill(\n    text=\"Alice is 30 and lives in Berlin.\",\n    schema_description=\"name (string), age (integer), city (string or null)\",\n)\nprint(result)\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Extracting a List of Structured Items"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Structured output also works for extracting multiple items from a document — for example, all entities, all line items in an invoice, or all events in a text."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import openai\nfrom pydantic import BaseModel\n\nclient = openai.OpenAI()\n\n\nclass LineItem(BaseModel):\n    description: str\n    quantity: int\n    unit_price_usd: float\n\n\nclass Invoice(BaseModel):\n    vendor: str\n    invoice_number: str\n    line_items: list[LineItem]\n    total_usd: float\n\n\nINVOICE_TEXT = \"\"\"\nInvoice #INV-2024-001 from Acme Corp.\n- 5x Widget A @ $10.00 each\n- 2x Widget B @ $25.50 each\nTotal: $101.00\n\"\"\"\n\ncompletion = client.beta.chat.completions.parse(\n    model=\"gpt-4o-mini\",\n    messages=[\n        {\"role\": \"system\", \"content\": \"Extract invoice details.\"},\n        {\"role\": \"user\",   \"content\": INVOICE_TEXT},\n    ],\n    response_format=Invoice,\n)\n\ninvoice = completion.choices[0].message.parsed\nprint(invoice.vendor)           # Acme Corp.\nprint(invoice.invoice_number)   # INV-2024-001\nfor item in invoice.line_items:\n    print(f\"  {item.quantity}x {item.description} @ ${item.unit_price_usd}\")\nprint(f\"Total: ${invoice.total_usd}\")\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Classification with Enums"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Structured output with an enum field is a reliable way to implement LLM-based classification. The model cannot output a category that is not in the allowed set."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import openai\nfrom pydantic import BaseModel\nfrom enum import Enum\n\nclient = openai.OpenAI()\n\n\nclass Sentiment(str, Enum):\n    POSITIVE = \"positive\"\n    NEGATIVE = \"negative\"\n    NEUTRAL = \"neutral\"\n\n\nclass SentimentResult(BaseModel):\n    sentiment: Sentiment\n    confidence: float    # 0.0–1.0\n    reason: str\n\n\ndef classify_sentiment(text: str) -> SentimentResult:\n    completion = client.beta.chat.completions.parse(\n        model=\"gpt-4o-mini\",\n        messages=[\n            {\"role\": \"system\", \"content\": \"Classify the sentiment of the user's text.\"},\n            {\"role\": \"user\",   \"content\": text},\n        ],\n        response_format=SentimentResult,\n    )\n    return completion.choices[0].message.parsed\n\n\nresult = classify_sentiment(\"This product is absolutely fantastic!\")\nprint(result.sentiment)    # Sentiment.POSITIVE\nprint(result.confidence)   # 0.95 (or similar)\nprint(result.reason)       # \"The text contains strong positive language...\"\n"
          }
        ]
      },
